as announced that the magazine will add two additional print
issues per year, restoring its status as a monthly magazine for the first t=
ime since the early 2000s. This comes on the heels of Vox Media=E2=80=99s r=
ecent expansion of its own print offerings, including tactile editions of T=
he Cut, the fashion/culture/etcetera digital arm of New York. Vice Media al=
so recently relaunched in print.

These print initiatives come with varying rationales: The Atlantic, which r=
ecently claimed to have achieved profitability, says print continues to dri=
ve subscription growth; Vox=E2=80=99s C.R.O. Geoff Schiller said The Cut wa=
s hoping to satisfy a new nostalgia for tangible products. Maybe, but in an=
 otherwise transformational moment in media, this pivot back to print feels=
 uninspired and even depressing=E2=80=94an investment in dissolving technol=
ogy, rather than a calculated risk on future models. Inevitably, whatever s=
mall amount of money they are making here pales in comparison to the opport=
unity cost they are
taking on.

