ght: 30px; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 0;">Greetings from Los Angeles,=
 and welcome back to In the Room, my twice-weekly private email on the medi=
a and media <i>people</i>. In tonight=E2=80=99s edition, we go back inside =
CBS News, where chief executive <b>Wendy McMahon</b> is now fielding <i>mul=
tiple </i>newsroom controversies as she prepares for a big meeting with her=
 future bosses <b>David Ellison </b>and <b>Jeff Shell</b>. <br/><br/><i>Als=
o mentioned in tonight=E2=80=99s email</i>: <b>Jeff Zucker</b>, <b>Jen DePr=
iest, Bill Owens</b>, <b>Tony Dokoupil</b>, <b>Ta-Nehisi Coates</b>, <b>Tro=
y Nehls</b>,<b> Kamala </b>and <b>Donald</b>, <b>Geoff Schiller</b>, <b>Jef=
frey Goldberg</b>, <b>Simone Swink</b>, <b>Rob Marciano</b>, and many more=
=E2=80=A6<br/><br/><i>But first</i>=E2=80=A6<br/><br/></p><ul style=3D"marg=
in:0;color:#000000;font-size:16px;line-height:30px;margin-top:0;margin-bott=
om:0;list-style-type:square;mso-special-format:bullet"><li><i>No more debat=
es</i>: CNN has announced that it will host a town hall with <b>Kamala Harr=
is </b>on October 23, the date it had initially proposed for a third presid=
ential debate, after determining that <b>Trump</b> is indeed unlikely to co=
mmit to any more face-offs with his opponent this cycle. That would seem to=
 officially put an end to any hope for a final debate before the election o=
n November 5 (though you never know). Meanwhile, the network is still holdi=
ng out hope that Trump might agree to a town hall that it could program bac=
k-to-back with the Kamala event. In the meantime, Trump has agreed to parti=
cipate in a <i>taped</i> event on =E2=80=9Cwomen=E2=80=99s issues=E2=80=9D =
on Fox News.</li><br/><li><i>Print is dead, long live print</i>: The Atlant=
ic=E2=80=99s <b>Jeffrey Goldberg </b>has announced that the magazine will a=
dd two additional print
issues per year, restoring its status as a <i>monthly</i> magazine for the =
first time since the early 2000s. This comes on the heels of Vox Media=E2=
=80=99s recent expansion of its own print offerings, including tactile edit=
ions of <i>The Cut</i>, the fashion/culture/etcetera digital arm of <i>New =
York</i>. Vice Media also recently relaunched in print.<br/><br/>These prin=
t initiatives come with varying rationales: <i>The Atlantic</i>, which rece=
ntly claimed to have achieved profitability, says print continues to drive =
subscription growth; Vox=E2=80=99s C.R.O. <b>Geoff Schiller </b>said <i>The=
 Cut</i> was hoping to satisfy a new nostalgia for tangible products. Maybe=
, but in an otherwise transformational moment in media, this pivot back to =
print feels uninspired and even depressing=E2=80=94an investment in dissolv=
ing technology, rather than a calculated risk on future models. Inevitably,=
 whatever small amount of money they are making here pales in comparison to=
 the opportunity cost they are
taking on.</li></ul>
